cc:Work.dc:description: ## Graphite Pencil Potentiometer ``` A potentiometer is a three-terminal resistor with a sliding or rotating contact that forms an adjustable voltage divider. ``` + [Read More: Wiki](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Potentiometer) Essentially, one end of a long resistive element with uniform resistivity is connected to one voltage level, and the opposite is connected to another. Along this long resistor, the measured voltage varies uniformly from the voltage at one end, to the voltage at the other. ### Graphite pencil The pencils you use can conduct electricity. So if we make a line on a paper, it is electrically conductive. But the resistance will be very high, so it is not a very good conductor. We shall try to make a potentiometer by making a thick line on paper, and attaching +6 to one end, and -6V to the other end using a pair of clips as shown If the line drawn has uniform thickness all along, the voltage at the center of the line measured using A1 will be close to 0. As you move towards the +6V end, the voltage will slowly increase till it reaches 6V. ## Additional experiments + Connect one end to GND(0V) , and the other to 5V. What is the voltage at the center? + Connect one end to GND, and the other to WG set to 1000 Hz . Observe the Graph's amplitude at different points. Change the graph visualization to the fast mode which shows the behaviour of A1 within a 5mS period. * *The readings of the A1 gauge will fluctuate wildly because WG is an oscillating voltage. However, you can observe the oscillations on the graph below the schematic quite easily. + Connect one end to 6V, and the other to WG set to 1000 Hz . Observe the Graph's amplitude. Explain why the average position has shifted from 0V. ### Voltmeter : A1 A1 is a voltmeter with +/-16V input range. It is set to +/-6V for this experiment It is also capable of measuring up to 1 million readings every second, and is also an oscilloscope input
